[0m[49m[39m  184, 186[0m:[39m[49m ### Prerequisites
[0m[49m[39m  185, 187[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  186, 188[0m:[39m[49m | Requirement | Details |
[0m[49m[39m  187, 189[0m:[39m[49m |-------------|---------|
[0m[49m[39m  188, 190[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Services** | Amazon SageMaker, Amazon S3, AWS Glue, Amazon DynamoDB, AWS Step Functions, Amazon CloudWatch |
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 189     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m | **IAM Permissions** | `sagemaker:CreateTrainingJob`, `sagemaker:CreateEndpoint`, `s3:GetObject`, `s3:PutObject`, `glue:StartJobRun`, `dynamodb:PutItem`, `dynamodb:GetItem`, `states:StartExecution` |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **IAM Permissions** | Resource-scoped: `sagemaker:CreateTrainingJob`, `CreateEndpoint` (scoped by tag conditions); `s3:GetObject`, `PutObject` on trajectory and model buckets only; `glue:StartJobRun` on `chemo-trajectory-etl*` jobs; `dynamodb:PutItem`, `GetItem` on patient-state and audit tables only; `states:StartExecution` on the RL pipeline state machine. Use separate roles for: training pipeline, inference endpoint, ETL, and clinician dashboard. |
[0m[49m[39m  190, 192[0m:[39m[49m | **BAA** | AWS BAA signed (required: treatment records are PHI) |
[0m[49m[39m  191, 193[0m:[39m[49m | **Encryption** | S3: SSE-KMS; DynamoDB: encryption at rest; SageMaker: KMS for training volumes and endpoints; all transit over TLS |
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 192     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m | **VPC** | Production: all services in VPC with VPC endpoints. SageMaker training and endpoints in private subnets. No public internet access for PHI-processing components. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **VPC** | All services in VPC with VPC endpoints. SageMaker training and endpoints in private subnets. No public internet access for PHI-processing components. Endpoints needed: S3 gateway (free), DynamoDB gateway (free), SageMaker Runtime interface (~$7.50/month/AZ), SageMaker API interface, Glue interface, Step Functions interface, CloudWatch interface, KMS interface. Budget ~$45-90/month for interface endpoints across 2-3 AZs. |
[0m[49m[39m  193, 195[0m:[39m[49m | **CloudTrail** | Enabled: log all API calls for HIPAA audit trail. Critical for tracking who accessed what patient data and when. |
[0m[49m[39m  194, 196[0m:[39m[49m | **Data Requirements** | Minimum 500-1000 complete treatment trajectories per regimen. More is better. Must include labs, dosing records, imaging, toxicity grades, and outcomes. |
[0m[49m[39m  195, 197[0m:[39m[49m | **Cost Estimate** | Training: $50-200 per training run (GPU instances, 4-12 hours). Inference endpoint: $200-800/month (ml.m5.xlarge). Storage and ETL: $100-500/month depending on data volume. |
[0m[49m[39m  196, 198[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  197, 199[0m:[39m[49m ### Ingredients
[0m[49m[39m  198, 200[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  199, 201[0m:[39m[49m | AWS Service | Role |
[0m[49m[39m  200, 202[0m:[39m[49m |------------|------|
[0m[49m[39m  201, 203[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon SageMaker** | RL model training (custom containers), model hosting for inference, experiment tracking |
[0m[49m[39m  202, 204[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon S3** | Trajectory dataset storage, model artifact registry, evaluation results |
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 203     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m | **AWS Glue** | ETL pipeline: EHR data to structured trajectories |
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 204     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m | **Amazon DynamoDB** | Real-time patient state vectors, recommendation audit trail |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      205[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Glue** | ETL pipeline: EHR data to structured trajectories (runs in customer VPC) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      206[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon DynamoDB** | Real-time patient state vectors, recommendation audit trail (append-only for audit records) |
[0m[49m[39m  205, 207[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Step Functions** | Training pipeline orchestration, retraining schedules |
[0m[49m[39m  206, 208[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon CloudWatch** | Monitoring: model drift, recommendation acceptance rates, outcome metrics |
[0m[49m[39m  207, 209[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS KMS** | Encryption key management for all PHI-containing stores |
[0m[49m[39m  208, 210[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  209, 211[0m:[39m[49m ### Code
[0m[49m[39m  210, 212[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  211, 213[0m:[39m[49m #### Walkthrough
[0m[49m[39m  212, 214[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  213, 215[0m:[39m[49m **Step 1: Extract treatment trajectories from EHR data.** The foundation of offline RL is historical data. You need complete treatment courses: every lab value, every dose administered, every imaging result, every toxicity event, assembled into a temporal sequence per patient. This is the hardest engineering step, not because the algorithms are complex, but because clinical data is messy. Labs arrive at irregular intervals. Imaging happens every 2-3 cycles, not every cycle. Toxicity is documented in free text that needs NLP extraction (see Chapter 8). Doses are sometimes modified mid-infusion. You need to align all of this into per-cycle state snapshots that the RL algorithm can consume. Skip this step or do it poorly, and your model learns from garbage.
[0m[49m[39m  214, 216[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  215, 217[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  216, 218[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION extract_trajectories(patient_ids, regimen):
[0m[49m[39m  217, 219[0m:[39m[49m     // For each patient who received this chemotherapy regimen,
[0m[49m[39m  218, 220[0m:[39m[49m     // construct a complete treatment trajectory: the sequence of
[0m[49m[39m  219, 221[0m:[39m[49m     // (state, action, reward, next_state) tuples across all cycles.
[0m[49m[39m  220, 222[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  221, 223[0m:[39m[49m     trajectories = empty list
[0m[49m[39m  222, 224[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  223, 225[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each patient_id in patient_ids:
[0m[49m[39m  224, 226[0m:[39m[49m         // Pull all relevant clinical data for this patient's treatment course.
[0m[49m[39m  225, 227[0m:[39m[49m         labs       = query lab results for patient_id during treatment period
[0m[49m[39m  226, 228[0m:[39m[49m         doses      = query medication administration records for regimen drugs
[0m[49m[39m  227, 229[0m:[39m[49m         imaging    = query radiology reports with tumor measurements
[0m[49m[39m  228, 230[0m:[39m[49m         toxicity   = query adverse event documentation (CTCAE grades)
[0m[49m[39m  229, 231[0m:[39m[49m         
[0m[49m[39m  230, 232[0m:[39m[49m         // Align data into per-cycle snapshots.
[0m[49m[39m  231, 233[0m:[39m[49m         // A "cycle" is one administration of the regimen (typically every 2-3 weeks).
[0m[49m[39m  232, 234[0m:[39m[49m         cycles = align_to_cycles(doses, regimen.cycle_length)
[0m[49m[39m  233, 235[0m:[39m[49m         
[0m[49m[39m  234, 236[0m:[39m[49m         trajectory = empty list
[0m[49m[39m  235, 237[0m:[39m[49m         FOR each cycle in cycles:
[0m[49m[39m  236, 238[0m:[39m[49m             // Build the state vector: what did the clinician know at decision time?
[0m[49m[39m  237, 239[0m:[39m[49m             state = {
[0m[49m[39m  238, 240[0m:[39m[49m                 anc:              most_recent_lab(labs, "ANC", cycle.start_date),
[0m[49m[39m  239, 241[0m:[39m[49m                 platelets:        most_recent_lab(labs, "PLT", cycle.start_date),
[0m[49m[39m  240, 242[0m:[39m[49m                 hemoglobin:       most_recent_lab(labs, "HGB", cycle.start_date),
[0m[49m[39m  241, 243[0m:[39m[49m                 creatinine:       most_recent_lab(labs, "CREAT", cycle.start_date),
[0m[49m[39m  242, 244[0m:[39m[49m                 bilirubin:        most_recent_lab(labs, "BILI", cycle.start_date),
[0m[49m[39m  243, 245[0m:[39m[49m                 tumor_size:       most_recent_imaging(imaging, cycle.start_date),
[0m[49m[39m  244, 246[0m:[39m[49m                 max_toxicity:     worst_toxicity_grade(toxicity, previous_cycle, cycle),
[0m[49m[39m  245, 247[0m:[39m[49m                 cycle_number:     cycle.number,
[0m[49m[39m  246, 248[0m:[39m[49m                 cumulative_dose:  sum of doses up to this cycle,
[0m[49m[39m  247, 249[0m:[39m[49m                 days_since_last:  days between this cycle and previous,
[0m[49m[39m  248, 250[0m:[39m[49m                 age:              patient.age,
[0m[49m[39m  249, 251[0m:[39m[49m                 bsa:              patient.body_surface_area,
[0m[49m[39m  250, 252[0m:[39m[49m                 performance:      patient.ecog_status
[0m[49m[39m  251, 253[0m:[39m[49m             }
[0m[49m[39m  252, 254[0m:[39m[49m             
[0m[49m[39m  253, 255[0m:[39m[49m             // The action: what dose was actually given?
[0m[49m[39m  254, 256[0m:[39m[49m             action = {
[0m[49m[39m  255, 257[0m:[39m[49m                 dose_fraction:    cycle.actual_dose / cycle.planned_dose,
[0m[49m[39m  256, 258[0m:[39m[49m                 delay_days:       cycle.actual_start - cycle.planned_start,
[0m[49m[39m  257, 259[0m:[39m[49m                 gcsf_given:       was G-CSF administered this cycle?
[0m[49m[39m  258, 260[0m:[39m[49m             }
[0m[49m[39m  259, 261[0m:[39m[49m             
[0m[49m[39m  260, 262[0m:[39m[49m             // The reward: how did things go?
[0m[49m[39m  261, 263[0m:[39m[49m             // This is computed retrospectively from what happened next.
[0m[49m[39m  262, 264[0m:[39m[49m             reward = compute_reward(state, action, next_cycle_state, outcome)
[0m[49m[39m  263, 265[0m:[39m[49m             
[0m[49m[39m  264, 266[0m:[39m[49m             append (state, action, reward) to trajectory
[0m[49m[39m  265, 267[0m:[39m[49m         
[0m[49m[39m  266, 268[0m:[39m[49m         append trajectory to trajectories
[0m[49m[39m  267, 269[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  268, 270[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN trajectories
[0m[49m[39m  269, 271[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  270, 272[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  271, 273[0m:[39m[49m **Step 2: Define the reward function.** This is where clinical judgment meets mathematical formulation. The reward function encodes what "good" means, and in chemotherapy dosing, "good" is a tradeoff between killing the tumor and not killing the patient. There's no single correct answer here. The weights reflect clinical values, and different institutions or oncologists might weight them differently. The key is making the tradeoff explicit and tunable, not hidden inside a black box. Get this wrong and your policy optimizes for the wrong thing. A reward that only penalizes toxicity will learn to never give chemotherapy. A reward that only rewards tumor shrinkage will learn to overdose patients.
[0m[49m[39m  272, 274[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  273, 275[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  274, 276[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION compute_reward(state, action, next_state, final_outcome):
[0m[49m[39m  275, 277[0m:[39m[49m     // Reward function for chemotherapy dose optimization.
[0m[49m[39m  276, 278[0m:[39m[49m     // Balances three objectives: tumor control, toxicity avoidance, treatment completion.
[0m[49m[39m  277, 279[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  278, 280[0m:[39m[49m     // --- Tumor response component ---
[0m[49m[39m  279, 281[0m:[39m[49m     // Positive reward for tumor shrinkage, negative for growth.
[0m[49m[39m  280, 282[0m:[39m[49m     // Only available when imaging exists (every 2-3 cycles typically).
[0m[49m[39m  281, 283[0m:[39m[49m     IF next_state.tumor_size is available:
[0m[49m[39m  282, 284[0m:[39m[49m         tumor_change = (next_state.tumor_size - state.tumor_size) / state.tumor_size
[0m[49m[39m  283, 285[0m:[39m[49m         // Negative change = shrinkage = good. Flip sign so shrinkage is positive reward.
[0m[49m[39m  284, 286[0m:[39m[49m         tumor_reward = -1.0 * tumor_change * TUMOR_WEIGHT
[0m[49m[39m  285, 287[0m:[39m[49m     ELSE:
[0m[49m[39m  286, 288[0m:[39m[49m         tumor_reward = 0  // no imaging this cycle, no tumor signal
[0m[49m[39m  287, 289[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  288, 290[0m:[39m[49m     // --- Toxicity penalty ---
[0m[49m[39m  289, 291[0m:[39m[49m     // Penalize grade 3+ adverse events. Grade 4 is penalized more heavily.
[0m[49m[39m  290, 292[0m:[39m[49m     // Grade 1-2 toxicities are expected and not penalized (they indicate the drug is working).
[0m[49m[39m  291, 293[0m:[39m[49m     toxicity_penalty = 0
[0m[49m[39m  292, 294[0m:[39m[49m     IF next_state.max_toxicity >= 4:
[0m[49m[39m  293, 295[0m:[39m[49m         toxicity_penalty = SEVERE_TOXICITY_PENALTY  // life-threatening, heavily penalized
[0m[49m[39m  294, 296[0m:[39m[49m     ELSE IF next_state.max_toxicity == 3:
[0m[49m[39m  295, 297[0m:[39m[49m         toxicity_penalty = MODERATE_TOXICITY_PENALTY  // significant but manageable
[0m[49m[39m  296, 298[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  297, 299[0m:[39m[49m     // --- Treatment discontinuation penalty ---
[0m[49m[39m  298, 300[0m:[39m[49m     // If the patient had to stop treatment entirely (not just delay),
[0m[49m[39m  299, 301[0m:[39m[49m     // that's usually the worst outcome: tumor progresses without treatment.
[0m[49m[39m  300, 302[0m:[39m[49m     discontinuation_penalty = 0
[0m[49m[39m  301, 303[0m:[39m[49m     IF treatment_was_discontinued(next_state):
[0m[49m[39m  302, 304[0m:[39m[49m         discontinuation_penalty = DISCONTINUATION_PENALTY  // large negative signal
[0m[49m[39m  303, 305[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  304, 306[0m:[39m[49m     // --- Dose intensity bonus ---
[0m[49m[39m  305, 307[0m:[39m[49m     // Small positive signal for maintaining dose intensity (relative dose intensity > 85%
[0m[49m[39m  306, 308[0m:[39m[49m     // is associated with better outcomes in many regimens).
[0m[49m[39m  307, 309[0m:[39m[49m     dose_intensity_bonus = 0
[0m[49m[39m  308, 310[0m:[39m[49m     IF action.dose_fraction >= 0.85:
[0m[49m[39m  309, 311[0m:[39m[49m         dose_intensity_bonus = DOSE_INTENSITY_WEIGHT
[0m[49m[39m  310, 312[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  311, 313[0m:[39m[49m     // Combine components. The weights (defined as constants) encode the clinical tradeoff.
[0m[49m[39m  312, 314[0m:[39m[49m     total_reward = tumor_reward - toxicity_penalty - discontinuation_penalty + dose_intensity_bonus
[0m[49m[39m  313, 315[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  314, 316[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN total_reward
[0m[49m[39m  315, 317[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  316, 318[0m:[39m[49m // Configuration: these weights are clinical value judgments, not learned parameters.
[0m[49m[39m  317, 319[0m:[39m[49m // They should be set in consultation with oncologists and may vary by regimen.
[0m[49m[39m  318, 320[0m:[39m[49m TUMOR_WEIGHT              = 10.0   // how much we value tumor response
[0m[49m[39m  319, 321[0m:[39m[49m MODERATE_TOXICITY_PENALTY = 3.0    // cost of a grade 3 adverse event
[0m[49m[39m  320, 322[0m:[39m[49m SEVERE_TOXICITY_PENALTY   = 15.0   // cost of a grade 4 adverse event (life-threatening)
[0m[49m[39m  321, 323[0m:[39m[49m DISCONTINUATION_PENALTY   = 25.0   // cost of having to stop treatment entirely
[0m[49m[39m  322, 324[0m:[39m[49m DOSE_INTENSITY_WEIGHT     = 1.0    // small bonus for maintaining therapeutic dose levels
[0m[49m[39m  323, 325[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  324, 326[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  325, 327[0m:[39m[49m **Step 3: Train the offline RL policy.** With trajectories constructed and rewards defined, you train a policy using conservative offline RL. The "conservative" part is critical: standard RL algorithms can be overconfident about actions they've never seen in the data. Conservative Q-Learning (CQL) addresses this by adding a penalty term that pushes down the estimated value of out-of-distribution actions. The result is a policy that stays close to historical clinical practice while improving where the data supports improvement. This is appropriate for healthcare: you want incremental, evidence-supported improvements, not radical departures from established practice.
[0m[49m[39m  326, 328[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  327, 329[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  328, 330[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION train_offline_rl_policy(trajectories, config):
[0m[49m[39m  329, 331[0m:[39m[49m     // Train a Conservative Q-Learning (CQL) policy from historical trajectories.
[0m[49m[39m  330, 332[0m:[39m[49m     // CQL is chosen because it's conservative by design: it won't recommend actions
[0m[49m[39m  331, 333[0m:[39m[49m     // that are far from what clinicians actually did in the training data.
[0m[49m[39m  332, 334[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  333, 335[0m:[39m[49m     // Convert trajectories to (s, a, r, s') tuples for training.
[0m[49m[39m  334, 336[0m:[39m[49m     dataset = []
[0m[49m[39m  335, 337[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each trajectory in trajectories:
[0m[49m[39m  336, 338[0m:[39m[49m         FOR i = 0 to length(trajectory) - 2:
[0m[49m[39m  337, 339[0m:[39m[49m             s      = trajectory[i].state
[0m[49m[39m  338, 340[0m:[39m[49m             a      = trajectory[i].action
[0m[49m[39m  339, 341[0m:[39m[49m             r      = trajectory[i].reward
[0m[49m[39m  340, 342[0m:[39m[49m             s_next = trajectory[i+1].state
[0m[49m[39m  341, 343[0m:[39m[49m             done   = (i == length(trajectory) - 2)  // last transition
[0m[49m[39m  342, 344[0m:[39m[49m             append (s, a, r, s_next, done) to dataset
[0m[49m[39m  343, 345[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  344, 346[0m:[39m[49m     // Initialize the Q-network.
[0m[49m[39m  345, 347[0m:[39m[49m     // Input: state vector (13+ features) concatenated with action vector (3 features).
[0m[49m[39m  346, 348[0m:[39m[49m     // Output: estimated cumulative future reward for that state-action pair.
[0m[49m[39m  347, 349[0m:[39m[49m     q_network = initialize neural network with:
[0m[49m[39m  348, 350[0m:[39m[49m         input_dim  = state_dim + action_dim
[0m[49m[39m  349, 351[0m:[39m[49m         hidden     = [256, 256, 128]  // three hidden layers
[0m[49m[39m  350, 352[0m:[39m[49m         output_dim = 1                // scalar Q-value
[0m[49m[39m  351, 353[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  352, 354[0m:[39m[49m     // CQL training loop.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      355[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Note: The action space here is discrete (30 combinations of dose x timing x G-CSF).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      356[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // For discrete CQL, you can enumerate all 30 actions and compute Q-values for each,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      357[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // then the CQL penalty pushes down the max Q across all actions relative to the Q of
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      358[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // the action actually taken. The random sampling formulation below is the continuous-action
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      359[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // variant included for generality. For this specific problem, discrete CQL is simpler.
[0m[49m[39m  353, 360[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each epoch in range(config.num_epochs):
[0m[49m[39m  354, 361[0m:[39m[49m         FOR each batch in sample_batches(dataset, config.batch_size):
[0m[49m[39m  355, 362[0m:[39m[49m             
[0m[49m[39m  356, 363[0m:[39m[49m             // Standard Bellman backup: what's the target Q-value?
[0m[49m[39m  357, 364[0m:[39m[49m             target_q = batch.rewards + config.gamma * max_q(q_network, batch.next_states)
[0m[49m[39m  358, 365[0m:[39m[49m             
[0m[49m[39m  359, 366[0m:[39m[49m             // CQL penalty: push down Q-values for actions NOT in the dataset.
[0m[49m[39m  360, 367[0m:[39m[49m             // This prevents overestimation of untested actions.
[0m[49m[39m  361, 368[0m:[39m[49m             random_actions = sample_random_actions(batch_size=len(batch))
[0m[49m[39m  362, 369[0m:[39m[49m             cql_penalty = mean(q_network(batch.states, random_actions)) 
[0m[49m[39m  363, 370[0m:[39m[49m                         - mean(q_network(batch.states, batch.actions))
[0m[49m[39m  364, 371[0m:[39m[49m             
[0m[49m[39m  365, 372[0m:[39m[49m             // Combined loss: standard TD error + CQL regularization.
[0m[49m[39m  366, 373[0m:[39m[49m             td_loss  = mean_squared_error(q_network(batch.states, batch.actions), target_q)
[0m[49m[39m  367, 374[0m:[39m[49m             loss     = td_loss + config.cql_alpha * cql_penalty
[0m[49m[39m  368, 375[0m:[39m[49m             
[0m[49m[39m  369, 376[0m:[39m[49m             update q_network to minimize loss
[0m[49m[39m  370, 377[0m:[39m[49m         
[0m[49m[39m  371, 378[0m:[39m[49m         // Evaluate on held-out trajectories every N epochs.
[0m[49m[39m  372, 379[0m:[39m[49m         IF epoch % config.eval_interval == 0:
[0m[49m[39m  373, 380[0m:[39m[49m             eval_score = evaluate_policy(q_network, held_out_trajectories)
[0m[49m[39m  374, 381[0m:[39m[49m             log metrics: epoch, td_loss, cql_penalty, eval_score
[0m[49m[39m  375, 382[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  376, 383[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN q_network  // the trained policy (argmax over Q-values gives the action)
[0m[49m[39m  377, 384[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  378, 385[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  379, 386[0m:[39m[49m **Step 4: Evaluate the learned policy.** You cannot deploy a policy without rigorous evaluation. Off-policy evaluation (OPE) estimates how well the learned policy would perform using only historical data. This is inherently uncertain (you're estimating counterfactuals), but it's the best you can do before a prospective trial. Multiple OPE methods should agree before you trust the result. If importance sampling says the policy is great but the model-based estimator says it's dangerous, you have a problem. Disagreement between estimators is a signal to investigate, not to pick the optimistic one.
[0m[49m[39m  380, 387[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  381, 388[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  382, 389[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION evaluate_policy(learned_policy, test_trajectories, behavior_policy):
[0m[49m[39m  383, 390[0m:[39m[49m     // Off-policy evaluation: estimate the value of the learned policy
[0m[49m[39m  384, 391[0m:[39m[49m     // using data generated by the behavior policy (historical clinical decisions).
[0m[49m[39m  385, 392[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  386, 393[0m:[39m[49m     // Method 1: Importance-weighted per-decision evaluation.
[0m[49m[39m  387, 394[0m:[39m[49m     // Weight each historical outcome by how likely the learned policy
[0m[49m[39m  388, 395[0m:[39m[49m     // would have been to take the same actions.
[0m[49m[39m  389, 396[0m:[39m[49m     is_estimates = []
[0m[49m[39m  390, 397[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each trajectory in test_trajectories:
[0m[49m[39m  391, 398[0m:[39m[49m         weight = 1.0
[0m[49m[39m  392, 399[0m:[39m[49m         cumulative_reward = 0
[0m[49m[39m  393, 400[0m:[39m[49m         FOR each (state, action, reward) in trajectory:
[0m[49m[39m  394, 401[0m:[39m[49m             // How likely is the learned policy to take this action?
[0m[49m[39m  395, 402[0m:[39m[49m             pi_prob    = learned_policy.action_probability(state, action)
[0m[49m[39m  396, 403[0m:[39m[49m             // How likely was the behavior policy (historical clinician) to take it?
[0m[49m[39m  397, 404[0m:[39m[49m             mu_prob    = behavior_policy.action_probability(state, action)
[0m[49m[39m  398, 405[0m:[39m[49m             
[0m[49m[39m  399, 406[0m:[39m[49m             // Clip the importance weight to avoid extreme values.
[0m[49m[39m  400, 407[0m:[39m[49m             // Extreme weights make the estimate unreliable.
[0m[49m[39m  401, 408[0m:[39m[49m             weight     = weight * clip(pi_prob / mu_prob, 0.01, 100.0)
[0m[49m[39m  402, 409[0m:[39m[49m             cumulative_reward = cumulative_reward + reward
[0m[49m[39m  403, 410[0m:[39m[49m         
[0m[49m[39m  404, 411[0m:[39m[49m         append weight * cumulative_reward to is_estimates
[0m[49m[39m  405, 412[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  406, 413[0m:[39m[49m     is_value = mean(is_estimates)
[0m[49m[39m  407, 414[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  408, 415[0m:[39m[49m     // Method 2: Fitted Q-Evaluation (FQE).
[0m[49m[39m  409, 416[0m:[39m[49m     // Train a separate Q-network to estimate the value of the learned policy.
[0m[49m[39m  410, 417[0m:[39m[49m     // This is more stable than importance sampling for long horizons.
[0m[49m[39m  411, 418[0m:[39m[49m     fqe_value = fitted_q_evaluation(learned_policy, test_trajectories)
[0m[49m[39m  412, 419[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  413, 420[0m:[39m[49m     // Method 3: Compare against the behavior policy baseline.
[0m[49m[39m  414, 421[0m:[39m[49m     behavior_value = mean(sum of rewards in each test trajectory)
[0m[49m[39m  415, 422[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  416, 423[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN {
[0m[49m[39m  417, 424[0m:[39m[49m         learned_policy_value_IS:  is_value,
[0m[49m[39m  418, 425[0m:[39m[49m         learned_policy_value_FQE: fqe_value,
[0m[49m[39m  419, 426[0m:[39m[49m         behavior_policy_value:    behavior_value,
[0m[49m[39m  420, 427[0m:[39m[49m         improvement_IS:           (is_value - behavior_value) / abs(behavior_value),
[0m[49m[39m  421, 428[0m:[39m[49m         improvement_FQE:          (fqe_value - behavior_value) / abs(behavior_value),
[0m[49m[39m  422, 429[0m:[39m[49m         agreement:                sign(is_value - behavior_value) == sign(fqe_value - behavior_value)
[0m[49m[39m  423, 430[0m:[39m[49m     }
[0m[49m[39m  424, 431[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  425, 432[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  426, 433[0m:[39m[49m **Step 5: Safety constraint enforcement.** No matter what the policy recommends, certain actions must be blocked. If the patient's ANC is below 1000, you don't give myelosuppressive chemotherapy. Period. These are hard constraints, not soft preferences. The safety layer sits between the policy output and the recommendation, vetoing any action that violates clinical safety rules. This is non-negotiable. The RL policy optimizes expected outcomes; the safety layer prevents catastrophic ones.
[0m[49m[39m  427, 434[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  428, 435[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  429, 436[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION apply_safety_constraints(recommended_action, current_state, safety_rules):
[0m[49m[39m  430, 437[0m:[39m[49m     // Hard safety constraints that override the RL policy.
[0m[49m[39m  431, 438[0m:[39m[49m     // These represent absolute clinical contraindications.
[0m[49m[39m  432, 439[0m:[39m[49m     // The policy is never allowed to violate these, regardless of expected reward.
[0m[49m[39m  433, 440[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  434, 441[0m:[39m[49m     violations = []
[0m[49m[39m  435, 442[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  436, 443[0m:[39m[49m     // Rule 1: Do not administer if ANC is critically low (neutropenia risk).
[0m[49m[39m  437, 444[0m:[39m[49m     IF current_state.anc < 1000:
[0m[49m[39m  438, 445[0m:[39m[49m         IF recommended_action.dose_fraction > 0:
[0m[49m[39m  439, 446[0m:[39m[49m             violations.append("ANC below 1000: must hold treatment")
[0m[49m[39m  440, 447[0m:[39m[49m             recommended_action.dose_fraction = 0  // hold cycle
[0m[49m[39m  441, 448[0m:[39m[49m             recommended_action.delay_days = 7     // recheck in 1 week
[0m[49m[39m  442, 449[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  443, 450[0m:[39m[49m     // Rule 2: Do not administer if platelets are critically low (bleeding risk).
[0m[49m[39m  444, 451[0m:[39m[49m     IF current_state.platelets < 75000:
[0m[49m[39m  445, 452[0m:[39m[49m         IF recommended_action.dose_fraction > 0.5:
[0m[49m[39m  446, 453[0m:[39m[49m             violations.append("Platelets below 75K: max 50% dose")
[0m[49m[39m  447, 454[0m:[39m[49m             recommended_action.dose_fraction = min(recommended_action.dose_fraction, 0.5)
[0m[49m[39m  448, 455[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  449, 456[0m:[39m[49m     // Rule 3: Reduce dose if bilirubin is elevated (hepatic clearance impaired).
[0m[49m[39m  450, 457[0m:[39m[49m     IF current_state.bilirubin > 1.5 * upper_normal_limit:
[0m[49m[39m  451, 458[0m:[39m[49m         IF recommended_action.dose_fraction > 0.75:
[0m[49m[39m  452, 459[0m:[39m[49m             violations.append("Elevated bilirubin: max 75% dose")
[0m[49m[39m  453, 460[0m:[39m[49m             recommended_action.dose_fraction = min(recommended_action.dose_fraction, 0.75)
[0m[49m[39m  454, 461[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  455, 462[0m:[39m[49m     // Rule 4: Do not exceed 100% of protocol dose (never escalate above standard).
[0m[49m[39m  456, 463[0m:[39m[49m     IF recommended_action.dose_fraction > 1.0:
[0m[49m[39m  457, 464[0m:[39m[49m         violations.append("Cannot exceed protocol dose")
[0m[49m[39m  458, 465[0m:[39m[49m         recommended_action.dose_fraction = 1.0
[0m[49m[39m  459, 466[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  460, 467[0m:[39m[49m     // Rule 5: Cumulative dose limits (e.g., anthracycline cardiotoxicity threshold).
[0m[49m[39m  461, 468[0m:[39m[49m     IF current_state.cumulative_dose > safety_rules.max_cumulative_dose:
[0m[49m[39m  462, 469[0m:[39m[49m         violations.append("Cumulative dose limit reached: discontinue agent")
[0m[49m[39m  463, 470[0m:[39m[49m         recommended_action.dose_fraction = 0
[0m[49m[39m  464, 471[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  465, 472[0m:[39m[49m     // Rule 6: Performance status too poor for treatment.
[0m[49m[39m  466, 473[0m:[39m[49m     IF current_state.performance >= 3:  // ECOG 3+ = limited self-care
[0m[49m[39m  467, 474[0m:[39m[49m         violations.append("ECOG >= 3: hold treatment, reassess goals of care")
[0m[49m[39m  468, 475[0m:[39m[49m         recommended_action.dose_fraction = 0
[0m[49m[39m  469, 476[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  470, 477[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN recommended_action, violations
[0m[49m[39m  471, 478[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  472, 479[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  473, 480[0m:[39m[49m **Step 6: Generate clinician-facing recommendation.** The final output is not "give 75% dose." It's a structured recommendation with reasoning, confidence, safety check results, and comparison to protocol-based dosing. The oncologist needs to understand why the system is recommending what it's recommending, and they need enough context to agree or disagree intelligently. This is decision support, not autonomous dosing. The clinician always makes the final call.
[0m[49m[39m  474, 481[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  475, 482[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  476, 483[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION generate_recommendation(patient_state, policy, safety_rules):
[0m[49m[39m  477, 484[0m:[39m[49m     // Generate a complete, explainable dosing recommendation for clinician review.
[0m[49m[39m  478, 485[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      486[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Validate state vector before policy inference.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      487[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Reject physiologically impossible values (catches EHR integration errors).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      488[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     validate_state(patient_state)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      489[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  479, 490[0m:[39m[49m     // Get the policy's raw recommendation.
[0m[49m[39m  480, 491[0m:[39m[49m     raw_action = policy.recommend(patient_state)
[0m[49m[39m  481, 492[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  482, 493[0m:[39m[49m     // Apply safety constraints (may modify the action).
[0m[49m[39m  483, 494[0m:[39m[49m     safe_action, violations = apply_safety_constraints(raw_action, patient_state, safety_rules)
[0m[49m[39m  484, 495[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  485, 496[0m:[39m[49m     // Get the protocol-based recommendation for comparison.
[0m[49m[39m  486, 497[0m:[39m[49m     // This is what standard guidelines would say given the same labs.
[0m[49m[39m  487, 498[0m:[39m[49m     protocol_action = standard_protocol_recommendation(patient_state)
[0m[49m[39m  488, 499[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  489, 500[0m:[39m[49m     // Compute confidence: how certain is the policy about this recommendation?
[0m[49m[39m  490, 501[0m:[39m[49m     // Low confidence = the state is far from training data or multiple actions have similar Q-values.
[0m[49m[39m  491, 502[0m:[39m[49m     confidence = policy.action_confidence(patient_state, safe_action)
[0m[49m[39m  492, 503[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  493, 504[0m:[39m[49m     // Identify the key state features driving this recommendation.
[0m[49m[39m  494, 505[0m:[39m[49m     // Which lab values or clinical factors most influenced the decision?
[0m[49m[39m  495, 506[0m:[39m[49m     key_drivers = policy.explain_recommendation(patient_state, safe_action)
[0m[49m[39m  496, 507[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  497, 508[0m:[39m[49m     recommendation = {
[0m[49m[39m  498, 509[0m:[39m[49m         recommended_dose_fraction:  safe_action.dose_fraction,
[0m[49m[39m  499, 510[0m:[39m[49m         recommended_delay_days:     safe_action.delay_days,
[0m[49m[39m  500, 511[0m:[39m[49m         recommended_gcsf:           safe_action.gcsf_given,
[0m[49m[39m  501, 512[0m:[39m[49m         confidence_score:           confidence,
[0m[49m[39m  502, 513[0m:[39m[49m         safety_violations:          violations,
[0m[49m[39m  503, 514[0m:[39m[49m         safety_constrained:         length(violations) > 0,
[0m[49m[39m  504, 515[0m:[39m[49m         protocol_recommendation:    protocol_action,
[0m[49m[39m  505, 516[0m:[39m[49m         differs_from_protocol:      safe_action != protocol_action,
[0m[49m[39m  506, 517[0m:[39m[49m         key_drivers:                key_drivers,
[0m[49m[39m  507, 518[0m:[39m[49m         patient_state_summary: {
[0m[49m[39m  508, 519[0m:[39m[49m             anc:           patient_state.anc,
[0m[49m[39m  509, 520[0m:[39m[49m             platelets:     patient_state.platelets,
[0m[49m[39m  510, 521[0m:[39m[49m             tumor_trend:   patient_state.tumor_size_trend,
[0m[49m[39m  511, 522[0m:[39m[49m             max_toxicity:  patient_state.max_toxicity,
[0m[49m[39m  512, 523[0m:[39m[49m             cycle:         patient_state.cycle_number
[0m[49m[39m  513, 524[0m:[39m[49m         }
[0m[49m[39m  514, 525[0m:[39m[49m     }
[0m[49m[39m  515, 526[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  516, 527[0m:[39m[49m     // Store recommendation for audit trail (regardless of whether clinician accepts it).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      528[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Audit trail requirements for clinical decision support:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      529[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // 1. Append-only: no updates or deletes permitted on recommendation records
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      530[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // 2. Tamper-evident: use S3 Object Lock (compliance mode) for archival copies
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      531[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // 3. Retention: minimum 7 years (malpractice statute of limitations varies by state)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      532[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // 4. Access: read-only for clinicians and compliance; write-only for recommendation engine
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      533[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // DynamoDB stores operational copies; S3 with Object Lock stores the compliance archive.
[0m[49m[39m  517, 534[0m:[39m[49m     store_recommendation(patient_state.patient_id, recommendation)
[0m[49m[39m  518, 535[0m:[39m[49m     
[0m[49m[39m  519, 536[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN recommendation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      537[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      538[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION validate_state(patient_state):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      539[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Reject physiologically impossible values before policy inference.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      540[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // These catch EHR integration errors, not clinical edge cases.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      541[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ASSERT 0 <= patient_state.anc <= 50000, "ANC out of physiological range"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      542[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ASSERT 0 <= patient_state.platelets <= 1000000, "Platelets out of range"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      543[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ASSERT 0 < patient_state.creatinine <= 30, "Creatinine out of range"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      544[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ASSERT 0 < patient_state.bilirubin <= 50, "Bilirubin out of range"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      545[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ASSERT patient_state.cycle_number >= 1, "Invalid cycle number"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      546[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // If any validation fails: do not generate recommendation, alert clinician.
[0m[49m[39m  520, 547[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  521, 548[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  522, 549[0m:[39m[49m > **Curious how this looks in Python?** The pseudocode above covers the concepts. If you'd like to see sample Python code that demonstrates these patterns using boto3, check out the [Python Example](chapter15.08-python-example). It walks through each step with inline comments and notes on what you'd need to change for a real deployment.
[0m[49m[39m  523, 550[0m:[39m[49m 
